th Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Scocca","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Concetta, Cosimo, Mauro, Vito.","Italian: from the feminine form of   Cocco  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Cocco","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Alberto, Americo, Luigi, Mario, Orlando, Rafael, Rocco, Aldo, Alfio, Angelo, Carmine, Erminio, Geno, Gino, Livio, Nicola, Remo.","Italian:","nickname from <i>cocco</i> ‘darling, most beloved son’, also ‘red’ and ‘egg’, or from a regional variant of <i>cucco</i> ‘cuckoo’, also ‘old man’."]},{"name":"Coca","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Manuel, Jorge, Mario, Carlos, Luis, Domingo, Eduardo, Gilberto, Rafael, Tomas, Alberto.","Spanish: habitational name from a place so named in Segovia province or from Coca de Alba or Coca de Huebra in Salamanca.","Italian: probably an altered form of   Cocca  , or possibly a variant of   Coco  ."]}]},{"name":"Margherita","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Greek.  See  <b>Margaret</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margaret","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margherita de Scocca was born about 1295, in Italy. She married Guglielmo Sanseverino Signore di  Montesano in 1323. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter."},"et":{"about 1295–":"umbes 1295–Surnud","1290–1341":"1290–1341","1340–1393":"1340–1393","–1361":"–1361","–1377":"–1377","1295–Female":"1295–Surnud","1377":"1377","1341":"1341","1340":"1340","1295":"1295","1361":"1361","1393":"1393","bet 1322 and 1325":"1323","about 1295":"umbes 1295","1290":"1290","Bassily, Hainaut, Belgium":"Bassilly, Hainaut, Belgia","Italy":"Itaalia"},"fi":{"about 1295–":"noin 1295–Kuollut","1290–1341":"1290–1341","1340–1393":"1340–1393","–1361":"–1361","–1377":"–1377","1295–Female":"1295–Kuollut","1377":"1377","1341":"1341","1340":"1340","1295":"1295","1361":"1361","1393":"1393","bet 1322 and 1325":"1323","about 1295":"noin 1295","1290":"1290","Bassily, Hainaut, Belgium":"Bassilly, Hainaut, Belgia","Italy":"Italia"},"fr":{"about 1295–":"environ 1295–Décédée","1290–1341":"1290–1341","1340–1393":"1340–1393","–1361":"–1361","–1377":"–1377","1295–Female":"1295–Décédée","1377":"1377","1341":"1341","1340":"1340","1295":"1295","1361":"1361","1393":"1393","bet 1322 and 1325":"1323","about 1295":"environ 1295","1290":"1290","Bassily, Hainaut, Belgium":"Bassilly, Hainaut, Belgique","Italy":"Italie","lifeSummary":"Margherita de Scocca est née environ 1295, à Italie. Elle a épousé Guglielmo Sanseverino Signore di  Montesano en 1323. Ils ont eu au moins 2 fils et 1 fille."},"de":{"about 1295–":"um 1295–Verstorben","1290–1341":"1290–1341","1340–1393":"1340–1393","–1361":"–1361","–1377":"–1377","12